\noindent where $\Phi$ is an additional free-parameter that was fit to the optical LCs.  Therefore, if a GRB-SN bump  has a value of $\Phi \approx 1$, this event can be considered as being powered entirely by EM emission from a magnetar central engine.  Conversely, for all events where $\Phi > 1$, additional sources of heating are needed to explain the luminosity of the SN phase, which based on previous investigations, is likely to the heating from the radioactive decay of nickel and cobalt into their daughter products.


